{"author":{"id":"856a2b67c1f7204e0cc1e7cc1a3b76ee0cc56ba44abdbb6c18fd58facbb42c04"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1417680408,"nonce":"TMYlnq9AZe/SL8E2uX2lY4snRW0=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY1NTUwMDE0","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/15#issuecomment-65550014"},"message":"@bgruening Also checkout http://mpds.stage.osdd.net/. I am not sure if it is well maintained. I do see some Weka wrappers.\n\nI was probably a really poor student when it comes down to my GSoC  for Galaxy, so I am afraid I might not be the best person to comment on. I would however like to share my experiences. It might  sound like a rant, but then my contribution to Galaxy during GSoC was close to zero. I blame myself for that, completely.\n\nI think I started off in a wrong wrong way. We had formalized working on eQTL pipelines. It was as such a great project, but 2-3 weeks down the line I realized I could have written wrappers even if I was not doing GSoC. The point being, it is more fun to work on problems of slightly higher difficulty. We did figure out at least two interesting projects and I think I failed miserably. That said, I still have some suggestions:\n1. We can start jotting down the ideas on a wiki, such as this one: http://gmod.org/wiki/GSoC\n2. Weekly calls? IRC is good but calls are more effective\n3. If the project involves knowing the Galaxy core base, it might be a good idea to encourage people to submit patches during the application period. I remember it took me couple of weeks to figure out how the core system works(I still don't!), and there maybe others like me.\n4. A project which is to be implemented from scratch is generally a good idea. Though I might be biased.\n5. In my opinion we should avoid offering writing wrappers, but I might be biased again.","files":null}]}